A clip making the rounds on social media pitched collectibles as a smarter bet than the stock market. The numbers looked compelling on their face. On The Money Guy Show segment &ldquo;Financial Advisors React to Jaw Dropping Money Clips,&rdquo; co-host Bo Hanson took the numbers apart and explained why the comparison falls apart under scrutiny.

The clip asserted that Pok&eacute;mon cards have generated a 20-year average return of 21.8% per year, totaling 3,261%, versus the S&P 500&rsquo;s 421% gain (8.79% annually). The presenter framed it as &ldquo;2.5 times better than the S&P 500.&rdquo;

Set alongside the actual index, the equity benchmark&rsquo;s long-run record is still substantial. The SPDR S&P 500 ETF ( NYSEARCA:SPY ) has climbed 509.56% over the roughly two-decade window from July 17, 2006 through July 14, 2026, with the ETF last printing $751.97. The 10-year figure alone is 248.34%. Real numbers, real liquidity, real dividends.

Bo Hanson&rsquo;s &ldquo;Math Crime&rdquo;

Hanson called the comparison a &ldquo;math crime.&rdquo; His core objection: the clip is stacking an aggregated collectibles number against a diversified equity index. As he put it, &ldquo;He is taking&hellip; the average across all American football cards&hellip; and comparing that to a basket of goods in the S&P 500.&rdquo;

Flip the exercise around and pit the collectibles average against individual equity winners, and the story changes. Hanson noted that names like Amazon, NVIDIA, and Tesla would &ldquo;smoke the numbers here&rdquo; over the same period. The collectibles pitch quietly compares a survivor-biased average of top cards against a broad index of 500 companies. Apples versus fruit salad.

The second layer of the flaw is the assumption that any given buyer actually captures the aggregate return. Hanson&rsquo;s point was direct: buying a $10 pack of Pok&eacute;mon cards and holding it for 20 years does not mean you &ldquo;got so lucky that one of the cards in your pack was so valuable that you recognize a 3,000% rate of return.&rdquo; Aggregate collectibles indexes are constructed from graded, high-condition, headline-grabbing cards. The pack in your closet is almost certainly not in that dataset.

Owning the S&P 500 through a low-cost fund works differently. In Hanson&rsquo;s framing, you &ldquo;own the 500 largest&hellip; best performing companies&hellip; in this country. It&rsquo;s not opening a pack of stocks and hoping you get lucky.&rdquo;

There is also the inflation drag no collectibles pitch mentions. The Consumer Price Index has moved from 308.417 in January 2024 to 333.952 in June 2026. The Fed&rsquo;s preferred gauge, Core PCE, sits at 130.082 as of May 2026, in the 90.9th percentile of its trailing 12-month range. Nominal appreciation numbers, whether on cards or stocks, need to be discounted by that ongoing erosion in purchasing power. Illiquid assets with wide bid-ask spreads and grading fees lose even more in the translation from paper gain to realized cash.

